VIRAL HEMORRHAGIC SEPTICEMIA, FISH - IRELAND
********************************************
Date: Fri, 18 Jul 1997 13:57:09 -0400
From: ProMED-mail <promed@usa.healthnet.org>
Via: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>
Source: Emergency report-Text of a fax received on 14 July 1997 from Dr. M.C.
Gaynor, Chief Veterinary Officer, Department of Agriculture, Food and
Forestry, Dublin
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Location: Clear Island, County Cork
No. of outbreaks: 1

Description of affected population: turbot in a farm on Clear Island, a small
island off the south-west coast of Ireland.
Diagnosis: isolation and characterisation of the virus.
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: European Community Reference
Laboratory for Fish Diseases, Aarhus, Denmark.
B. Diagnostic tests used: tests laid down in Commission Decision 92/532/EEC.
C. Causal agent: viral haemorrhagic septicaemia virus.
Source of agent/origin of infection: under investigation. This is the first
case of viral hemorrhagic septicemia identified in Ireland.
Control measures during reporting period: approved zone status for Clear
Island has been suspended. Strict movement controls are in operation at the
infected farm. Marketing of fish has temporarily ceased.
